RAMMY DISTRIBUTED FABRIC VALIDATION LADDER

The purpose of these tests is not merely to prove that RAMMY can
"distribute jobs."

The purpose is to progressively demonstrate that:

    memory
    process identity
    model state
    execution locality
    fault recovery
    distributed residency

are all behaving as one coordinated computational organism.

Each stage acts as both:
    a milestone
and:
    a smoke test for future large-scale AI workloads.


[01] Fabric discovery
     All nodes automatically discover and map each other.

[02] Unified memory report
     RAMMY reports total pooled fabric RAM across all nodes.

[03] Remote page allocation
     One node allocates memory physically resident on another node.

[04] Remote page read/write
     Nodes transparently read and write remote pages.

[05] Distributed object allocation
     A single object spans multiple physical machines.

[06] Objects larger than one node
     RAMMY allocates memory larger than any individual machine can hold.

[07] Page ownership tracking
     Every page has explicit ownership and residency metadata.

[08] Replicated pages
     Pages exist redundantly across nodes.

[09] Replica verification
     RAMMY verifies page integrity across replicas.

[10] Node death detection
     RAMMY detects dead or unreachable nodes automatically.

[11] Data survival after node death
     Replicated pages survive node failure.

[12] Automatic re-replication
     RAMMY restores redundancy after failures.

[13] Topology awareness
     RAMMY maps bandwidth and latency between nodes.

[14] Locality-aware placement
     Frequently accessed pages migrate closer to active computation.

[15] Hot/cold page classification
     RAMMY tracks memory heat over time.

[16] Hot page migration
     Frequently used pages dynamically relocate.

[17] Cold page relocation
     Cold pages move away from premium memory regions.

[18] Distributed page cache
     Nodes cache remote pages intelligently.

[19] Cache invalidation correctness
     Stale remote copies invalidate correctly after writes.

[20] Lease-based ownership
     RAMMY prevents conflicting distributed writes.

[21] Distributed allocator
     Applications request fabric-wide allocations directly.

[22] Memory pressure balancing
     RAMMY redistributes allocations when nodes become saturated.

[23] Distributed checkpointing
     Runtime state snapshots across the fabric.

[24] Distributed checkpoint restore
     Restore distributed state after restart.

[25] Process migration
     A live process moves between nodes.

[26] Process identity continuity
     Migrated processes retain identity and state.

[27] Execution locality optimization
     Processes relocate toward memory-heavy regions.

[28] Failure-transparent execution
     Running workloads survive node failure.

[29] Coordinator failover
     Cluster leadership transfers automatically.

[30] Distributed file residency
     Large files remain distributed across pooled memory.

[31] Large embedding residency
     Massive embedding indexes exceed single-node capacity.

[32] Retrieval system over pooled memory
     Distributed RAG-style retrieval runs across fabric memory.

[33] Distributed tensor residency
     Tensor shards remain resident across nodes.

[34] Tensor placement optimization
     RAMMY places tensors according to topology and locality.

[35] Activation passing
     Nodes exchange compact activations instead of entire model weights.

[36] Distributed KV cache
     Transformer KV cache spans multiple nodes.

[37] Long-context KV growth
     Context windows exceed single-node memory limits.

[38] Toy transformer inference
     A small transformer executes across multiple nodes.

[39] Layer pipeline execution
     Transformer layers execute in distributed stages.

[40] Distributed model loading
     A model larger than one node loads successfully.

[41] Quantized 70B model residency
     A real 70B-class model resides across pooled fabric memory.

[42] Stable token streaming
     Distributed inference streams tokens continuously.

[43] Inference under memory pressure
     RAMMY continues inference while relocating cold memory.

[44] Mid-generation node failure
     Kill a node during inference.

[45] Inference recovery
     Generation resumes using replicas/checkpoints.

[46] Distributed Stable Diffusion residency
     Diffusion weights distribute across pooled memory.

[47] Distributed image generation pipeline
     Text encoder, UNet, and VAE execute across fabric-connected nodes.

[48] Distributed video generation prototype
     Multi-frame generation spans pooled memory fabric.

[49] 1TB pooled memory demonstration
     Multiple ordinary machines expose terabyte-scale unified memory.

[50] Flagship demonstration
     5 recycled desktops
     25GbE
     quantized 70B model
     stable inference
     live node failover
     distributed residency
     pooled memory
     topology-aware execution

     This demonstrates that RAMMY is not merely coordinating machines.

     It demonstrates that:
         memory is pooled
         execution is migratory
         model state is distributed
         failures are survivable
         and the fabric behaves as one computational organism.

